Analysis On Mental Health In Fatal Police Shootings¶

By Caitlynn Li

Introduction¶

In this tutorial, I would like to determine what the significant features of a victim in a fatal police shooting would be in order to determine whether or not they showed any signs of mental illness. I chose this dataset because it offers a lot of insight regarding all the fatal policing shootings from 2015 to 2021. Furthermore, mental health is a very important topic, especially in the midst of a pandemic, and can provide us with insights regarding police shootings. Mental illness controls more aspects of our lives than people would like to show, and this tutorial sets out to discover exactly what features have a significant relationship with mental illness. However, I think it is important to note that none of the records are of police brutality. To my knowledge, the shootings occurred because the victim posed as a serious threat to the safety of the police officers and others.

About The Data¶

Below, we are loading in the dataset. I got the dataset from the Washington Post, which you can access here. The data contains every fatal police shooting in the United States by a police officer in the line of duty since January 1, 2015. The data documents fatal shootings that occur when an on duty police officer shoots and kills a civilian. The dataset does not document the deaths of people in police custody, shootings from an off duty police officers, or non-shooting deaths.

These are the meanings behind each column, taken from the Washington Post github:

  • id: a unique identifier for each victim
  • name: the name of the victim
  • date: the date of the fatal shooting in YYYY-MM-DD format
  • manner_of_death: if they were just shot or shot and tasered
  • armed: if the victim was carrying a weapon
    • undetermined: it is not known whether or not the victim had a weapon
    • unknown: the victim was armed, but it is not known what the object was
    • unarmed: the victim was not armed
  • age: the age of the victim
  • gender: the gender of the victim
  • race:
    • W: White, non-Hispanic
    • B: Black, non-Hispanic
    • A: Asian
    • N: Indigenous
    • H: Hispanic
    • O: Other
    • None: unknown
  • city: the municipality where the fatal shooting took place.
  • state: two-letter postal code abbreviation
  • signs of mental illness: News reports have indicated the victim had a history of mental health issues, expressed suicidal intentions or was experiencing mental distress at the time of the shooting.
  • threat_level: The threat_level column was used to flag incidents for the story by Amy Brittain in October 2015. http://www.washingtonpost.com/sf/investigative/2015/10/24/on-duty-under-fire/ As described in the story, the general criteria for the attack label was that there was the most direct and immediate threat to life. That would include incidents where officers or others were shot at, threatened with a gun, attacked with other weapons or physical force, etc. The attack category is meant to flag the highest level of threat. The other and undetermined categories represent all remaining cases. Other includes many incidents where officers or others faced significant threats.
  • flee: News reports have indicated the victim was moving away from officers
    • Foot
    • Car
    • Not fleeing
  • body_camera: News reports have indicated an officer was wearing a body camera and it may have recorded some portion of the incident.
  • latitude and longitude: the location of the shooting expressed as WGS84 coordinates, geocoded from addresses.
  • is_geocoding_exact: reflects the accuracy of the coordinates.

def armed(x):
    if x == "unarmed":
        return 0
    elif x == "toy weapon":
        return 1
    elif "BB" in x or "pellet" in x or "bow" in x or "bean" in x or "nail" in x or "pistol" in x:
        return 3
    elif "sharp" in x or "axe" in x or "shard" in x or "pick" in x or "sword" in x or "spike" in x or "cut" in x or\
    "blade" in x or "cleaver" in x or "saw" in x or "fork" in x or "fork" in x or "bow" in x or "bayonet" in x:
        return 4
    elif "gun" in x:
        return 5
    elif "fireworks" in x or "explosive" in x or "grenade" in x:
        return 6
    else:
        return 2

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning¶

I decided to perform feature selection using the Chi Square Test. The Chi Square test of independence tells us if there's is a significant relationship between two categorical variables. Since the majority of my data was categorical, I decided this was a suitable method. I want to determine the significant features in predicting whether a victim showed signs of a mental illness or not. The Chi Square test of independence is also very suitable for feature selecting as it will tell us which variables have a significant relationship. When performing our chi squared test, we will be testing the following hypotheses:

Null Hypothesis: There is no relationship between the two variables.
Alternative Hypothesis: There is a relationship between the two variables.

In [1238]:
#Here we are performing the chi square test between our target variable signs_of_mental_illness, and all categorical variables, using a p-value of .05
chi2_check = []
for i in categorical_vars:
    if chi2_contingency(pd.crosstab(data['signs_of_mental_illness'], data[i]))[1] < 0.05:
        chi2_check.append('Reject Null Hypothesis')
    else:
        chi2_check.append('Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis')
res = pd.DataFrame(data = [categorical_vars, chi2_check] 
             ).T 
res.columns = ['Column', 'Hypothesis']
print(res)

            Column                      Hypothesis
0             date  Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis
1  manner_of_death          Reject Null Hypothesis
2            armed          Reject Null Hypothesis
3              age          Reject Null Hypothesis
4           gender          Reject Null Hypothesis
5             race          Reject Null Hypothesis
6            state          Reject Null Hypothesis
7     threat_level          Reject Null Hypothesis
8             flee          Reject Null Hypothesis
9      body_camera          Reject Null Hypothesis

As we can see from our table, we are able to reject the null hypothesis for all variables except date. indicating there is a significant relationship between signs_of_mental_illness and those variables.

However, since we have multiple classes within each categorical variable, we are unable to determine exactly which class is responsible for the relationship. In order to effectively determine exactly which feature is responsible, we need to perform a OneHotEncoding. A OneHotEncoding will simply tell us if a feature is present or not in a particular observation. By doing this we will be able to pinpoint exactly which feature is responsible.

It is also important to note that comparing multiple classes against each other will compound the error rate of a false positive. This means that if we start off with a p-value of .05, there is a 5% chance of a false positive at the first class. However, as we go on to evaluate the next class, the error rate of a false positive will become 10%. In order to combat this, we will use the Bonferroni-adjusted method. This is where the p-value becomes the original p-value divided by the number of classes for each categorical variable.

In [1239]:
check = {}
#Performing OneHotEncoding on the variables that displayed a significant relationship with signs_of_mental_illness
for i in res[res['Hypothesis'] == 'Reject Null Hypothesis']['Column']:
    #Creating the onehotencoding columns
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(data[i])
    #calculating adjusted p-value
    bon_p_value = 0.05/data[i].nunique()
    
    #Performing chi square test of independence for each class
    for series in dummies:
        if chi2_contingency(pd.crosstab(data['signs_of_mental_illness'], dummies[series]))[1] < bon_p_value:
            check['{}-{}'.format(i, series)] = 'Reject Null Hypothesis'
        else:
            check['{}-{}'.format(i, series)] = 'Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis'
res_chi_ph = pd.DataFrame(data = [check.keys(), check.values()]).T
res_chi_ph.columns = ['Pair', 'Hypothesis']

preds = log_model.predict_proba(X_test[significant_chi])[:,1]
fpr, tpr, threshold = roc_curve(y_test, preds)
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
plt.title('Receiver Operator Characteristic')
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, 'b', label = 'AUC = {}'.format(round(roc_auc, 2)))
plt.legend(loc = 'lower right')
plt.plot([0,1], [0,1], 'r--')
plt.xlim([0,1])
plt.ylim([0,1])
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.show()

As we can see our AUC did improve, though not by much. It still tells us that our model is more accurate when using our selected features.

Conclusion¶

In this tutorial we wanted to see which characteristics of victims to fatal police shootings could be attributed to their mental state. In the exploratory data analysis section of our tutorial, we played around with the data to see if there were any trends or hypotheses we could from about our data. During this step, we discovered that the victim's mental state seemed to have played a role in whether or not they decided to flee. This prompted us to ask the question: What other features may have been influenced by the victim's mental state? In our machine learning section, we used the chi square test of independence to determine exactly which characteristics of a fatal police shooting is related to the victim's mental state. At the end we were able to determine that the victim's manner of death, age, weapon yielded, whether or not they fled, among other variables all maintained a significant relationship with the victim's mental state. We found that by only using these variables to predict the victim's mental state, we were able to obtain a higher rate of success compared to when we used all variables in our prediction model.
